   GLOBAL FIX: To prevent this class of bugs, developers should always ensure
   that the destination buffer is large enough to accommodate the data being
   copied. Instead of using `memcpy` with a fixed size, it is better to use
   functions that are bounds-checked or to pass the size explicitly. In C++,
   using `std::string` or `std::vector<char>` would prevent such buffer
   overflows by automatically managing memory and handling resizing. If raw
   arrays must be used, then a safe wrapper or a static analyzer should be
   employed to catch such errors at compile time. Additionally, clearly defining
   the intent of `memcpy` operations by explicitly specifying the size of the
   destination buffer rather than the size of the entire containing structure is
   crucial. Use `sizeof(destination_buffer)` instead of
   `sizeof(enclosing_struct)` if copying into a member of the struct.
